{"cursor":"33421","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox weapon |name=Sturmgewehr 44 |image= |caption=StG44 |origin=\n|type=Assault rifle  |is_ranged=yes  |service=September 1943âMay 1945 (Nazi Germany) |used_by=See\n[[#Users|Users]] |wars=World War II, appeared in post-1945 conflicts around the\nworld  |designer=Hugo Schmeisser |design_date=1942\n|manufacturer=C. G. Haenel Waffen und Fahrradfabrik CITEFA |unit_cost=\n|production_date=September 1943 |number=425,977 |variants=  |spec_label= |weight= unloaded with magazine Sturmgewehr\n44 (StG44) D1854/3 Manual / loaded The full weight of the StG44 with\nempty magazine & sling is 4.62 kg according to the original 'Sturmgewehr 44\n(StG44) D1854/3 Manual', and each 7.92mm S.m.E. Kurz round weighes in at 17.05\ngrams a piece according to the original 7.92 Kurz Polte drawings, so with 30\nrounds in the magazine the fully loaded weight of the StG44 will be 5.13\nkg. |length= |part_length= |width= |height=  |cartridge= 7.92Ã33mm Kurz, Jane's Guns\nRecognition Guide, Ian Hogg & Terry Gander, Harper & Collins Publishers, 2005,\nPage 287 (aka. 7.9mm Kurz or Pistolenpatrone 43) |action=Gas-operated,\ntilting bolt, full auto or semi-auto |rate=550-600 rounds/min |velocity=\n|range=300 m (automatic) 600 m (semi-automatic) Rusiecki, Stephen M.,\n[http://books.google.se/books?id=xCoTjyrLTM8C&pg=PA361 In final defense of the\nReich: the destruction of the 6th SS Mountain Division \"Nord\"] ISBN 978-1-59114-744-\n2, p.361 |max_range= |feed=30-round detachable box magazine\n|sights=Adjustable sights, rear: V-notch; front: hooded post }} The 'StG 44'\n(Sturmgewehr 44, literally \"storm (or assault) rifle (model of 19)44\" was an\nassault rifle developed in Nazi Germany during World War II that was the first\nof its kind to see major deployment and is considered by many historians to be\nthe first modern assault rifle. Ed Ezell, Ian Hogg, Chris Bishop, John\nWeeks, Vincent DiMaio, David Westwood, and WHB Smi